On Friday May 21 Vancouver shows up to stand in solidarity with land defenders at Fairy Creek. We gather on the unceded territories of the xʷməθkʷəy̓əm (Musqueam), Sḵwx̱wú7mesh (Squamish), and səlilwətaɬ (Tsleil-Waututh) Nations.
⁠
We stand with Elder Bill Jones
We stand with Kati George-Jim⁠
We stand with Aya Clappis⁠
We stand with all front line defenders who have been holding it down for the past 9 months.⁠
⁠
We stand to end colonial violence and un-checked resource extraction within our last critical endangered ecosystems. ⁠
⁠
We stand against the RCMP's establishment of unlawful exclusion zones and against the tactics employed by the RCMP, BC NDP, and BC FORESTRY.⁠
⁠
We reject BC NDP, John Horgan's and BC Forestry's campaign of misinformation.⁠
⁠

⁠

⚠️ TO BE CUT ⚠️ Looper Creek has been marked for logging by @westernforestproducts It represents the last intact section of the Caycuse Watershed on Dididaht Territory. The company has recently gained two road building approvals, one of which would precipitate eventual clear cutting of the entire area, similar to what in the Upper Caycuse (site of @tjwatt ‘s famous before and after images of old growth logging) has experienced over the past two years.

These road approvals cut directly through a stand of monumental cedar trees that represent some of the largest remaining in the watershed.

On top of these Western Forest Products approvals for the Teal Jones group is in the process of securing permits to clear-cut three valley-bottom sections of old growth forest along the Caycuse River Valley.

We cannot let these corporations get what they want.

Because their agenda is colonial Ecocide.

We want to protect these trees but we cannot do it without your help. 

Join us on the frontlines.

In celebration of World Orangutan  Day. 
GLOBAL ONLINE PREMIERE! Once only chance to watch our new documentary: Eyes of the Orangutan.

This hard hitting film - which took us four years to make - offers a unique insight into the dark world of Wildlife Tourism and its impact on one of our closest living relatives.

On August 22nd we will be doing an exclusive global online screening, which will include a Q&A with the film-makers, world-renowned experts, and our partners, below. 

📍 Register now: www.eyesoftheorangutan.com

Eyes of the Orangutan is a Terra Mater Factual Studios production, in partnership with Aaron Gekoski, Environmental Photojournalist, Chris Scarffe Film & Photography, Will Foster-Grundy Cinematographer, Damian Antochewicz and supported by Louise Potts, Damon Copeland, Jeffrey Hartog and Richard Jonathan Chambers.

Made in close cooperation with BOS Schweiz, BOS Foundation, Jakarta Animal Aid Network (JAAN), Born Free Foundation and additional PR support from Borneo Orangutan Survival UK - BOS UK, BOS-USA, Borneo Orangutan Survival (BOS) Australia and Orangutan Outreach.

Thank you to Shannon Elizabeth and Simon Borchert of the Shannon Elizabeth Foundation, who will be hosting the event.

Also a huge thanks to everyone who supported my Wildlife Tourism GoFundMe page. Your donations helped make this film a reality. 

📍 Support animals rescued from the industry: born2bewild.org

📍 Report animals suffering for tourism: https://www.bornfree.org.uk/raise-the-red-flag

#EyesOfTheOrangutan
